Turkey is expanding diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to enter the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps in Asia, is one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-renaissance style.
This is at least what the tourist guides tell you.
The building is riding between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the ceiling at once, there is no doubt about the size of the company of what was the most western passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a delay in the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway running in Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But the imperial ambitions of Germany sank during the first world war.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the ice borders of the cold war, has passed
British and dominating forces moved out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station too.
In 1917 a munitions train broke out destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then he has slowly gone out of the way, far out of history.
But today, this railway outlet for Anatolia and all the points to the east, need - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-largest diplomatic horizons.
The ruling party of Justice and Development - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the ice borders of the cold war, has passed.
Now there is a new policy of commitment.
The Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the car bed for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of AKP's main foreign policy experts, Turkish deputy Suat Kinikioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a skirmish race along the tracks that produced the old world cadences of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intended to turn their backs on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary movement in Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the general district of AKP, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built shopping centres and power pastries, where managers in business-completes - both men and women - meet to make early morning contracts.
Suat Kinikioglu could be a center-right politician from almost every other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
"The purpose of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbours.
The cold war was an anomaly," he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its territory.
Today you must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't the case of one or the other.
They must be both.
"But certainly at a certain point, "I ask, "Will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want to face that choice."
Then he points out that almost everyone I spoke to here has recited in memory: the links of not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are of benefit to Europe and the United States as much as they are for Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, Europe as a whole can metaphorically travel those railway lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Again at Hydarpasha station, after another night in white, I think of those two German gentleman Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's Middle-Eastern ambitions can now be, in large part, in the hands of Turkey.
And while I'm waiting at the terminal for the ferry that brings me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that those days Turkey has always been called "the sick man of Europe".
At the same time, there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent it was supposed to advance on this fascinating country.
