In order for the draft Constitution to be adopted, it should obtain half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the election seats and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced a crushing victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had claimed on the night between Sunday and Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously," he had assured the Ecuadorians in the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did her Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The election, which took place calmly according to the election observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points aimed at consolidating the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution enshrines the power of the state over the economy, reserving it the "development planning" of a country that essentially lives from the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently their currency.
Designed by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives greater power to the Head of State, who may be elected for two consecutive terms of office of four years, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced its intention to take advantage of this amendment and to reintroduce its candidacy for a new mandate in February 2009.
The Constitution also states that health and education services are free of charge, which the president has begun to promote in this country 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American drug operations.
